Introduction to IconGrid
************************

IconGrid is a Shell tool to align Workbench icons on a virtual grid.
Its purpose is similar to the "Clean Up" feature of Workbench, but it
does not arrange the Icons in a random way.

To use IconGrid, you first position the Icons at the approximate
positions where you would like them, snapshot them with Workbench and
call IconGrid. IconGrid will move them to the nearest grid position and
shapshot them there.

IconGrid uses the bottom edge of the icons for vertical alignment and
the middle of the icon for horizontal alignment. This means, you can
easily align icons in a very good looking way: with centered columns
and filename-aligned rows.


@EndNode

@Node "Usage" "IconGrid/Usage"
@Next "ToolManager"
@Prev "Introduction"
@Toc "Main"

Usage of IconGrid
*****************

IconGrid is a Shell program with the following template:

     FILE/A/M,GRIDSIZE/N

@{b}FILE@{ub}
     are the names of one or more icons that shall be aligned on the
     (non-visible) grid.  Use the filenames without the
     ".info"-extension. The icons must have already been snapshotted at
     the approximate position you would like to see them. If you do not
     snapshot them, the position of the last snapshot will be used for
     grid-aligning, or you will get an error message if the icon
     position is not fixed.

@{b}GRIDSIZE@{ub}
     is an optional numeric argument to specify the distance between
     the grid lines in pixels. Defaults to 10. Use this if the default
     grid is too wide or too fine for your task.


@EndNode

@Node "ToolManager" "IconGrid/ToolManager"
@Next "Author"
@Prev "Usage"
